{
  "text": "A particularly robust example is the effects of stressors and maladaptive behaviors on telomeres. Telomeres are the DNA strands that cap the ends of DNA and protect the precision of DNA replication. Telomeres shorten with each cell replication and shorter telomeres are associated with aging. The percentage of shorter telomeres that one has is associated not only with aging and processes of senescence, but with increased liability to a very wide range of medical and psychiatric illnesses. Adversity in early life is associated with shorter telomeres as is an increasing number of depressive episodes. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] Many of the common accompaniments of depression are associated with shorter telomeres, including poor diet, a lack of exercise, and a lack of mindfulness/meditation or the feeling that one is making a positive contribution to others in accomplishing one's life goals. Interestingly, nihilistic and pervasive anger is also associated with shorter telomeres. Lithium directly increases the enzyme telomerase, which adds to telomere length, [CITATION_5] so augmentation of antidepressants with lithium may have a triple benefit of: (i) preventing episode recurrence; (ii) increasing telomere length; and (iii) increasing BDNF and neurogenesis with consequent increases in hippocampal and cortical volume.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "2277059",
    "[CITATION_2]": "38331356",
